==Old English==
===Etymology===
From Germanic, from Indo-European ''*upér-'', a comparative form of ''*upo''.

''Germanic cognates:'' Old Saxon [[oƀar]] (Dutch [[over#Dutch|over]]), Old High German [[ubar]] (German [[über]]), Old Norse [[yfir]] (Swedish [[över]]), Gothic [[𐌿𐍆𐌰𐍂]].

''Indo-European cognates:'' Greek [[ὕπερ]], [[ὑπέρ]], Latin [[super]], Old Irish [[for]] (Welsh [[gor-]]).

